":"Tortworth, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"nl":{"about 1501–":"circa 1501–Overleden","1501–Female":"1501–Overleden","1532–Female":"1532–Overleden","1501–Male":"1501–Overleden","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1501":"1501","1532":"1532","1620":"1620","about 1501":"circa 1501","1571":"1571","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","Tortworth, Gloucestershire, England":"Tortworth, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"en":{"about 1501–":"about 1501–Deceased","1501–Female":"1501–Deceased","1532–Female":"1532–Deceased","1501–Male":"1501–Deceased","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1501":"1501","1532":"1532","1620":"1620","about 1501":"about 1501","1571":"1571","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","Tortworth, Gloucestershire, England":"Tortworth, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hicks","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Hick  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This is a widespread surname in England, and is also common in southwest and southern Wales.","German: patronymic from   Hick  . Compare   Hix  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Higgs","meanings":["English:","variant of   Hicks   with voicing of <i>-k-</i>.","variant of <b>Higg</b>, itself from Middle English <i>Higge</i> (a pet form of Hugh), with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. Compare   Higson  ."]},{"name":"Hix","meanings":["English and German: variant of   Hicks  .","German: from a pet form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’ as the first element."]},{"name":"Hick","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, from the Middle English personal name <i>Hikke</i>, a rhyming pet form of <i>Ricard</i>, a Norman-Picard form of   Richard  . The substitution of <i>H-</i> as the initial resulted from the inability of the English to cope with the velar Norman <i>R-</i>. Compare   Hitch  .","German, Flemish, and Dutch: from <i>Hicke</i>, a pet form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’ as the first element.","German: from a pet form (see   Huck  ) of the personal name   Hugo  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":48,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":57,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":68,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705206,"age":70,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705210,"age":99,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705212,"age":119,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Hicks was born about 1501, in Tortworth, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Mother Hicks."},"et":{"about 1501–":"umbes 1501–Surnud","1501–Female":"1501–Surnud","1532–Female":"1532–Surnud","1501–Male":"1501–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1501":"1501","1532":"1532","1620":"1620","about 1501":"umbes 1501","1571":"1571","15